ds, the National Archives, and private collections of charitable organizations, this book examines not only the attitudes of British officials towards South Asians in their midst, but also the actual application of these attitudes in decisions pertaining to them. This fascinating book will be of particular interest to scholars and general readers of imperialism, immigration as well as British and Indian social history.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aEast IndiansxSocial conditionsy19th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aEast IndianszGreat BritainxSocial conditionsy19th century. 0aImperialismxHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial classesxHistoryy19th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aSocial classeszGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aSocial integrationxHistoryy19th centuryzGreat Britain. 0aSocial integrationzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 4aStudies in Imperialism 2017. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh  aBritish Isles.  aBritish bigotry.  aBritish institutions.  aIndia office.  aIndian culture.  aIndian students.  aKumar Shri Ranjitsinjhi.  aLondon City Mission.  aNational Indian Association.  aSouth Asians.  aStrangers' Home for Asiatics.  acivilising mission.  agovernment scholarships.  ahierarchical empire.  aimperial identity.  alegal identity.  asocial class.1 aWainwright, A. Martin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertManchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagez978311128363040uhttps://doi.org/10.7765/978152612141740uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781526121417423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781526121417/original  a978-3-11-128363-0  Manchester University Press 1986 - 2013 eBook Packagec1986d2013  aGBV-deGruyter-alles